AN  - 862596271; 201109636
AB  - Using representative survey data of 5,466 'titular' (i.e. named after the states or republics of residence) & Russian respondents, this study examines the relationship between ethnic & republic identification in 28 cities in five autonomous republics of the Russian Federation, in Ukraine & in the Ukrainian Republic of Crimea. In accordance with Social Dominance Theory, ethnic & republic identification turned out to be positively & more strongly correlated among dominant than among subordinate groups. Group-size ratio was not found to affect identification patterns. At the contextual level, perceived cultural threat & the endorsement of multiculturalism & minority rights moderated the association between ethnic & republic identification of both groups. Intergroup differences in identification patterns were smaller in cities where both support for multiculturalism & the perception of cultural threat were higher. These results also shed light on the developing relationships between Russian & titular populations in the former Soviet Union. Adapted from the source document.
